# Expressions

We should be as precise as possible. For example, things like `if (myValue)` would only be valid if the value would be a boolean.

We refer here concretely to code that is evaluated, pieces of code that produce a value, such as conditional statements or ternary expressions.

We should stop checking against truthy or falsy values and evaluate like this instead:

```ts
export function isObject(val: unknown): boolean {
  return Object.prototype.toString.call(val) === '[object Object]';
}

export function isEmptyObject(val: unknown): boolean {
  return isObject(val) && Object.keys(val).length === 0;
}

export function isNumber(val: unknown): boolean {
  return typeof val === 'number';
}

export function isString(val: unknown): boolean {
  return typeof val === 'string';
}

export function isBoolean(val: unknown): boolean {
  return typeof val === 'boolean';
}

const myAnyOrNull: unknown | null = null;
const myAnyOrUndefined: unknown | undefined = undefined;
const myAnyOrNullOrUndefined: unknown | undefined | null = {};
const myString = '';
const myArray: unknown[] = [];

if (isObject(myAnyOrNullOrUndefined)) {
}
if (isEmptyObject(myAnyOrNullOrUndefined)) {
}
if (myAnyOrNull !== null) {
}
if (myAnyOrUndefined !== undefined) {
}
if (myAnyOrNullOrUndefined != null) {
}
if (isNumber(myAnyOrNullOrUndefined)) {
}
if (isString(myAnyOrNullOrUndefined)) {
}
if (myString.length === 0) {
}
if (isBoolean(myAnyOrNullOrUndefined)) {
}
if (Array.isArray(myArray)) {
}
if (myArray.length === 0) {
}
```

Of course the naming used in the examples above would not be valid as a convention, since we should not include types in the actual names. Same way we use the type `unknown`, in order to be effective with the example.

Note that curly braces are enforced for compound statements like the `if` ones from the example. According to Douglas Crockford "Braces should be used around all statements, even single statements, when they are part of a control structure, such as an if or for statement. This makes it easier to add statements without accidentally introducing bugs".

You should consider sometimes if a `switch` statement is more suitable for your implementation needs. If so, remember that it must contain a `default` statement group, even if it contains no code and also that non-empty statement groups (`case ...`) may not fall through and need a `break` whereas empty ones are allowed to fall through.

```ts
switch (x) {
  case X:
  case Y:
    doSomething();
    break;
  default:
}
```

We always use strict equality (`===`) in these cases, instead of loose equality (`==`). However, the expression `myAnyOrNullOrUndefined != null` is not loose, it specifically checks if the variable is null or undefined. An old JS trick.

Following these concretions avoids unintended truthy evaluations and unexpected behaviors that could lead to bugs and therefore prevents a lot of runtime errors.

Let us understand why with a good example:

```ts
const myArray: unknown[] = [];
let counter = 0;

incrementCounter(myArray);

// Outputs 1 when the intended value should be 0.
console.log(counter);

function incrementCounter(value: unknown[]) {
  // Incorrect: unintended truthy evaluation with an empty array.
  // It should be `if (value.length > 0) {}`.
  if (value) {
    counter++;
  }
}
```

The only exception to this coding good practice would be the boolean primitive, since its value is not evaluated and directly tells us if we have `true` or `false` there.

And last but not least: when evaluating code with logical operators we should use the nullish coalescing operator (`??`) instead of the logical OR operator (`||`), since in the latter the left-hand operand is checked against any falsy value whereas in the former it is only checked against `null` or `undefined`, which is what we usually want. If that is not what we want, then, and only then, we should use the OR one (`||`).

An example:

```ts
const userCount = 0;

// Using logical OR (||) with 0 as a valid value.
const wrongDefaultUserCount: number = userCount || 19;

// Using nullish coalescing (??) with 0 as a valid value.
const rightDefaultUserCount: number = userCount ?? 10;

// Output: 19 (incorrect result):
console.log(wrongDefaultUserCount);
// Output: 0 (correct result):
console.log(rightDefaultUserCount);
```
